    title: "Outsourcing the Remembering",
    text: "At my niece's graduation last summer, I found myself watching a row of parents experience the ceremony entirely through the screens of their phones. As their children crossed the stage, they crouched, zoomed and framed, and I would have felt smug about my own empty hands had I not spent the previous evening doing precisely the same thing at a restaurant, photographing a dessert I can no longer describe. We have become a species that documents compulsively, and the awkward question, one psychologists have finally begun to answer, is what all this recording is doing to the faculty it is supposed to serve.\n\nThe early findings were not flattering. In a much-cited study, visitors to a museum were asked to photograph some exhibits and merely observe others; the next day, they remembered the photographed objects less accurately, a result its author called the photo-taking impairment effect. The interpretation seemed obvious: the camera becomes a subcontractor, and the mind, trusting the device to store the experience, quietly declines to do the work itself. Yet the same research programme produced a complication that is usually left out of the retelling. Participants who zoomed in on a detail of an object remembered the whole object better, including the parts outside the frame. Photography, it appears, does not damage memory as such; inattentive photography does. The lens can be a substitute for looking, but it can also be a discipline that intensifies it.\n\nDefenders of the camera roll will object that offloading memory is hardly a modern vice. We have always delegated remembering to external stores, to diaries, letters, portraits and the anecdotes of relatives, and civilisation is largely the history of such delegation. I accept the point, but it undersells what has changed. A diarist selects; a Victorian family sat for one portrait a decade. The modern archive is produced without effort and, crucially, consulted without ceremony, which mostly means not at all. Studies of photo libraries suggest the majority of images are never deliberately viewed again. We are not outsourcing memory to an archive so much as posting it into a void that happens to have excellent storage.\n\nThe distinction matters because remembering is not retrieval but reconstruction. The old photograph album, assembled by hand, captioned and argued over at the kitchen table, was a machine for rehearsing a family's story, and the rehearsal, not the paper, did the mnemonic work. A camera roll of eleven thousand unsorted images offers no such rehearsal; it is raw footage awaiting an editor who never arrives.\n\nI have not renounced my phone, and this essay is not a sermon. But I have changed my habits in two small ways: I photograph less and look longer, and once a month I sit down and actually edit, deleting ruthlessly and captioning what survives. The dessert, wherever it is, remains lost. My niece's expression as she took her certificate, which I watched with my hands in my pockets, I can still see.",
