    id: "c-rmc3-02",
    title: "The Gentle Tyranny of the Nudge",
    text: "Somewhere in Whitehall, a civil servant is deciding how you will die. Not when, and not painfully, but in one narrow administrative sense: whether, at the moment your driving licence is renewed, the organ-donation box will be ticked for you unless you object, or left blank unless you volunteer. The difference sounds trivial. It is not. Countries that presume consent achieve donor registration rates several times higher than countries that request it, and the population's underlying views on donation barely differ. The lever that moves those millions of decisions is not argument, or incentive, or law. It is the default setting, and defaults are the flagship of what its architects call nudging: the design of choices so that human inertia works for us instead of against us.\n\nThe case for nudging is seductive, and I should confess at the outset that I am half seduced. Traditional policy tools are blunt. Bans breed resentment and black markets; taxes fall hardest on the poor; information campaigns assume a diligent citizen who reads leaflets, an assumption falsified by every leaflet ever printed. The nudge, by contrast, preserves freedom on paper. Nobody is forbidden the sugary drink at the checkout; it has merely been moved to a lower shelf, and the fruit to eye level. If we must be influenced, and the behavioural evidence says we are influenced by choice architecture whether anyone designs it or not, then surely it is better that the architect be benevolent and accountable rather than a supermarket's profit motive.\n\nAnd yet the word 'accountable' is doing suspicious work in that sentence. A tax is visible; it is debated, voted on, resented in the open. A default is quiet by design, and its quietness is precisely what makes it effective. When influence works best on those who scrutinise least, a government has acquired a tool that succeeds in proportion to its citizens' inattention, and it takes considerable optimism to believe such a tool will only ever be pointed at worthy targets. The same techniques that auto-enrol workers into pensions also auto-enrol them into subscriptions they never wanted; industry learned the grammar of the nudge long before regulators did, and calls its version a dark pattern.\n\nThe deeper objection is not that nudges might be misused but that even their proper use changes the relationship between state and citizen. A government that persuades me treats me as a reasoner who may refuse; a government that rearranges my cafeteria treats me as a statistical tendency to be managed. Perhaps that is realism. Human beings are statistical tendencies a good deal of the time, and I would rather be nudged into a pension than argued into poverty. But a democracy that routes its policy around deliberation, because deliberation is slow and inertia is reliable, should not be surprised if the deliberative muscles of its citizens atrophy from disuse.\n\nMy own resolution is unheroic: nudge, but noisily. Publish every default, justify it, and make the opt-out one obvious click. Influence that can survive being announced is guidance. Influence that depends on going unnoticed deserves the older, harsher name we used to have for it.",
