    id: "c-rmc3-03",
    title: "In Praise of the Difficult Hobby",
    text: "My grandfather kept bees, badly, for forty years. The honey was sporadic, the stings were not, and no accountant could have made the enterprise respectable. When I asked him, towards the end, why he had persisted, he looked at me as though I had asked why he persisted in having friends. The question of what a pastime is for would not have occurred to him, and I have come to think that our inability to leave that question alone is one of the quieter afflictions of the age.\n\nConsider what has happened to the word 'hobby' itself. It now arrives with an apology attached. We describe our pastimes as guilty pleasures, or justify them as networking, self-care or, most tellingly, as side hustles, embryonic businesses awaiting monetisation. The sourdough must be photographed, the photography must build a following, the following must eventually convert. A leisure activity that produces nothing sellable and improves no metric has begun to feel, to many people, vaguely illegitimate, like an unexplained gap on a CV. This is new. It is also, I want to argue, exactly backwards.\n\nThe pastimes that repay us most, the evidence increasingly suggests, are the ones that resist us. Psychologists studying recovery from work find that genuine restoration comes not from collapse in front of a screen, which leaves people no less depleted, but from what they call mastery experiences: absorbing, moderately difficult activities in which progress is perceptible but never complete. The violin, the allotment, the chess club, the terrible watercolours. Difficulty is not the price of the benefit; difficulty is the mechanism of the benefit. An activity hard enough to demand full attention crowds out rumination, the mind's habit of chewing on workplace grievances, and it is rumination, more than hours worked, that predicts burnout.\n\nThere is a subtler gift as well. The difficult hobby is one of the last places where an adult is permitted to be a beginner. Professional life rewards the concealment of incompetence; we learn to bluff fluency in meetings and to describe our weaknesses, in interviews, as excessive perfectionism. The beginner at the pottery wheel has no such refuge. The clay collapses publicly, and nothing depends on it, and slowly one relearns a skill that childhood had and adulthood loses: how to be visibly bad at something without being diminished by it. I can think of few capacities more useful, or more transferable, though transferability is precisely the wrong reason to seek it.\n\nAnd there lies the trap in writing any defence of hobbies. Each benefit I list, resilience, recovery, humility, is one step from becoming a productivity argument, and the reader is one step from taking up beekeeping in order to become a more effective quarterly performer. The optimisation has a way of creeping back in through the door marked wellbeing. So let me end where my grandfather would have started. The bees were not for anything. That was the point, and the honey, when it came, was sweeter for being beside it.",
